                     <handNote xml:id="h2" script="Ethiopic">The script appears uneven, tending to broadly spaced and irregularly slanted letters. A few distinctive features of the handwriting appear throughout the Ms.:<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h3" script="Ethiopic">
-	occasionally, the form of 'one' (፩, triangular upwards-oriented, but with dashes) reminiscent of the archaic one (e.g., fol. 12ra l.2)<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h4" script="Ethiopic">
-	the characters ወ, መ, ሠ are often formed on a slant, the lower left side extends to the base line while the upper right part extends to the upper limit<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h5" script="Ethiopic">
-	in some cases the vowel marker of ሎ is attached directly to the right leg at the upper part (e.g., fol. 8ra l.7, 18va l. 5)<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h6" script="Ethiopic">
-	ሮ, ሬ and ፌ are of peculiar shape (e.g., fol 16ral. 9, 11, 14).<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h7" script="Ethiopic">
